Based on my investigation, I've identified the exact bug and can now provide the diagnosis.

## Summary

The test fails with "macro arguments parsing error" when macro arguments contain quoted strings (e.g., `.include(glob=true,something="test")`). The parser incorrectly truncates the argument string at the opening quote, parsing only `option="` instead of the full `option="value"`.

---

**ROOT CAUSE:** `src/ucl_parser.c:1826-1835` — In the macro argument parser's state machine, when state 1 (inside quotes) is active, the code advances the pointer via `ucl_chunk_skipc()` but fails to increment `args_len`. This causes all characters inside quoted strings to be skipped from the argument length calculation, resulting in truncated, unparseable argument strings like `option="` instead of `option="value"`.

**LOCAL FIX:** Add `args_len++;` in state 1 (before line 1834, after the check for the closing quote):
```c
case 1:
    /* We have quote character, so skip all but quotes */
    if (*p == '"' && *(p - 1) != '\\') {
        state = 0;
    }
    args_len++;  // ADD THIS LINE - count all characters inside quotes
    if (chunk->remain == 0) {
        goto restore_chunk;
    }
    ucl_chunk_skipc (chunk, p);
    break;
```

**GLOBAL FIX:** Refactor the macro argument extraction to use a pointer-based substring approach instead of manual character counting. Currently, the parser manually counts characters while tracking state, which is error-prone when multiple parsing contexts (quotes, parentheses) interact. Replace the state machine logic with: (1) find the opening `(`, (2) scan forward counting nested parentheses while respecting quotes, (3) extract the substring directly without character-by-character counting. This eliminates the state machine coordination problem entirely and makes quote handling implicit in the substring extraction rather than a special case.
